#: src/rust-2018/the-compiler/incremental-compilation-for-faster-compiles.md:1
msgid "Incremental Compilation"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/the-compiler/incremental-compilation-for-faster-compiles.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.24](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.24-brightgreen.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/the-compiler/incremental-compilation-for-faster-compiles.md:5
msgid ""
"Back in September of 2016, we [blogged about Incremental Compilation]"
"(https://blog.rust-lang.org/2016/09/08/incremental.html). While that post "
"goes into the details, the idea is basically this: when you’re working on a "
"project, you often compile it, then change something small, then compile "
"again. Historically, the compiler has compiled your entire project, no "
"matter how little you’ve changed the code. The idea with incremental "
"compilation is that you only need to compile the code you’ve actually "
"changed, which means that that second build is faster."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/the-compiler/incremental-compilation-for-faster-compiles.md:14
msgid ""
"This is now turned on by default. This means that your builds should be "
"faster! Don’t forget about `cargo check` when trying to get the lowest "
"possible build times."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/the-compiler/incremental-compilation-for-faster-compiles.md:18
msgid ""
"This is still not the end story for compiler performance generally, nor "
"incremental compilation specifically. We have a lot more work planned in the "
"future."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/the-compiler/incremental-compilation-for-faster-compiles.md:22
msgid ""
"One small note about this change: it makes builds faster, but makes the "
"final binary a bit slower. For this reason, it's not turned on in release "
"builds."
msgstr ""
